## ❌ WRONG: Automatic Search Pattern

**MUST NOT use this pattern (causes API call on every input):**

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: API called on every input change
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isInitialLoad) {
    fetchData(); // ← Called on every searchKeyword change
  }
}, [searchCondition, searchKeyword, joGunMberSta]); // ← Dependencies cause automatic calls

// ❌ WRONG: Input triggers API automatically
<input
  type="text"
  value={searchKeyword}
  onChange={(e) => {
    setSearchKeyword(e.target.value); // State change triggers useEffect → API call
  }}
/>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ **Performance Issue**: API called on every keystroke
   - User types "홍길동" → 3 API calls (홍, 홍길, 홍길동)
   - Unnecessary server load
   - Increased network traffic

2. ❌ **User Experience Issue**:
   - List updates while user is still typing
   - Loading states appear during typing
   - Distracting and unprofessional

3. ❌ **Resource Waste**:
   - Unnecessary API calls consume server resources
   - Network bandwidth wasted
   - Database queries executed unnecessarily

4. ❌ **Inconsistent Behavior**:
   - Search conditions trigger API automatically
   - Table filters use Debounce (800ms)
   - Confusing for users and developers

**Real-world Example of the Mistake:**

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: This was the actual mistake in useMemberList.ts
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isInitialLoad) {
    fetchMembers(); // ← Called on EVERY keystroke
  }
}, [searchCondition, searchKeyword, joGunMberSta]); // ← Dependencies cause automatic calls

// Result: User types "홍길동" → 3 API calls
// - "홍" → API call
// - "홍길" → API call
// - "홍길동" → API call
```

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Remove search conditions from dependencies
useEffect(() => {
  fetchMembers(); // Initial load only
}, []);

// ✅ CORRECT: Explicit search handler
const handleSearch = () => {
  setCurrentPage(1);
  fetchMembers(); // API call only on explicit action
};
```

