## 🔄 Step-by-Step Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Set Up State and Refs

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: State structure
const [members, setMembers] = useState<Item[]>([]);
const [totalElements, setTotalElements] = useState(0);
const [totalPages, setTotalPages] = useState(0);
const [currentPage, setCurrentPage] = useState(1);
const [isInitialLoad, setIsInitialLoad] = useState(true);

const [filters, setFilters] = useState({
  userId: "",
  userNm: "",
  // ... other filters
});

const [searchCondition, setSearchCondition] = useState("1");
const [searchKeyword, setSearchKeyword] = useState("");

// ✅ CORRECT: Refs for stable references
const filtersRef = useRef(filters);
const searchConditionRef = useRef(searchCondition);
const searchKeywordRef = useRef(searchKeyword);
const initialFetchDoneRef = useRef(false); // First fetch done (page-change effect: avoid duplicate call)
const initialLoadDoneRef = useRef(false); // First load done (filter effect: preserve page when returning from detail)

// Update refs when state changes
useEffect(() => {
  filtersRef.current = filters;
}, [filters]);

useEffect(() => {
  searchConditionRef.current = searchCondition;
}, [searchCondition]);

useEffect(() => {
  searchKeywordRef.current = searchKeyword;
}, [searchKeyword]);
```

### Step 2: Create Fetch Function with useCallback

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Fetch function with minimal dependencies
const fetchMembers = useCallback(async () => {
  try {
    setLoading(true);
    const startIndex = (currentPage - 1) * pageSize;

    const params = {
      // Use refs, not state directly
      searchCondition: searchConditionRef.current,
      searchKeyword: searchKeywordRef.current,
      length: pageSize.toString(),
      start: startIndex.toString(),
      filterUserId: filtersRef.current.userId || undefined,
      // ... other filters
    };

    const response = await Service.getList(params);
    setMembers(response.data || []);
    setTotalElements(response.recordsTotal || 0);
    setTotalPages(Math.ceil((response.recordsTotal || 0) / pageSize));
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Data fetch failed:", err);
  } finally {
    setLoading(false);
    setIsInitialLoad(false);
    initialFetchDoneRef.current = true;
    initialLoadDoneRef.current = true;
  }
}, [currentPage, pageSize]); // ⚠️ Only page-related dependencies
```

### Step 3: Create Ref for Fetch Function

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Ref for fetchMembers
const fetchMembersRef = useRef(fetchMembers);
useEffect(() => {
  fetchMembersRef.current = fetchMembers;
}, [fetchMembers]);
```

### Step 4: Set Up Initial Load and Page Change

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Initial load (one call only)
useEffect(() => {
  fetchMembers();
}, []);

// ✅ CORRECT: Page change triggers API (only after first fetch done; prevents duplicate call on mount)
useEffect(() => {
  if (!initialFetchDoneRef.current) return;
  fetchMembers();
}, [currentPage, fetchMembers]); // ⚠️ MUST NOT include isInitialLoad
```

**Why ref gate:** If `isInitialLoad` is in the dependency array, when the first fetch completes and `setIsInitialLoad(false)` runs, this effect runs again and calls fetch a second time. Using `initialFetchDoneRef` and removing `isInitialLoad` from deps ensures fetch runs only when `currentPage` actually changes after the initial load.

