## 🚫 Common Mistakes to Avoid

### Mistake 1: Adding Search Conditions to useEffect Dependencies

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Search conditions in dependencies (text inputs)
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isInitialLoad) {
    fetchData();
  }
}, [searchCondition, searchKeyword]); // ❌ Causes automatic calls

// ❌ WRONG: Select fields also cause automatic calls!
useEffect(() => {
  if (targetList.length > 0 && targetGbn) {
    fetchData(); // ❌ Called when targetGbn changes!
  }
}, [targetList, targetGbn]); // ❌ targetGbn in dependencies causes automatic calls
```

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Remove ALL search conditions from dependencies
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(); // Initial load only
}, []);

// ✅ CORRECT: Use explicit handler for ALL search conditions
const handleSearch = () => {
  setCurrentPage(1);
  fetchData(); // API called only on explicit action
};
```

**⚠️ CRITICAL**: Remember to remove BOTH text inputs AND select/dropdown fields from dependencies!

### Mistake 2: Putting isInitialLoad in Fetch-Triggering Effect Dependencies

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: isInitialLoad in page-change effect dependencies
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isInitialLoad) {
    fetchMembers();
  }
}, [currentPage, fetchMembers, isInitialLoad]); // ❌ When isInitialLoad flips to false, effect runs again → duplicate API call

// ❌ WRONG: isInitialLoad in filter debounce effect dependencies
useEffect(() => {
  if (isInitialLoad) return;
  const timer = setTimeout(() => {
    setCurrentPage(1);
    fetchMembersRef.current();
  }, 800);
  return () => clearTimeout(timer);
}, [filters.userId, filters.userNm, isInitialLoad]); // ❌ When isInitialLoad flips to false, effect runs → 800ms later page resets to 1 (breaks detail→list page preservation)
```

**Why this is wrong:** When the first fetch completes, `setIsInitialLoad(false)` runs. Both effects re-run because `isInitialLoad` is in their dependency array. The page-change effect calls fetch again (duplicate call). The filter effect schedules an 800ms timer that calls `setCurrentPage(1)` and fetch, so when returning from detail to list with `?page=2`, the preserved page is overwritten to 1.

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use refs; remove isInitialLoad from dependencies
const initialFetchDoneRef = useRef(false);
const initialLoadDoneRef = useRef(false);

// In fetch function finally block:
initialFetchDoneRef.current = true;
initialLoadDoneRef.current = true;

// Page-change effect: gate with ref; dependency without isInitialLoad
useEffect(() => {
  if (!initialFetchDoneRef.current) return;
  fetchMembers();
}, [currentPage, fetchMembers]);

// Filter effect: gate with ref; dependency without isInitialLoad
useEffect(() => {
  if (!initialLoadDoneRef.current) return;
  const timer = setTimeout(() => {
    setCurrentPage(1);
    fetchMembersRef.current();
  }, 800);
  return () => clearTimeout(timer);
}, [filters.userId, filters.userNm]); // filter fields only
```

### Mistake 3: Calling API in Input/Select onChange

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: API call in text input onChange
<input
  value={searchKeyword}
  onChange={(e) => {
    setSearchKeyword(e.target.value);
    fetchData(); // ❌ API call on every keystroke
  }}
/>

// ❌ WRONG: API call in select onChange (same problem!)
<select
  value={targetGbn}
  onChange={(e) => {
    setTargetGbn(e.target.value);
    fetchData(); // ❌ API call on every select change
  }}
>
```

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Text input - only update state
<input
  value={searchKeyword}
  onChange={(e) => setSearchKeyword(e.target.value)} // State only, NO API call
  onKeyPress={(e) => {
    if (e.key === "Enter") {
      handleSearch(); // Explicit API call
    }
  }}
/>

// ✅ CORRECT: Select - only update state
<select
  value={targetGbn}
  onChange={(e) => setTargetGbn(e.target.value)} // State only, NO API call
>
  {targetList.map((target) => (
    <option key={target.code} value={target.code}>
      {target.codeNm}
    </option>
  ))}
</select>

// ✅ CORRECT: Explicit search handler
const handleSearch = () => {
  setCurrentPage(1);
  fetchData(); // API called only on explicit action
};
```

### Mistake 4: Mixing Automatic and Explicit Search

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Both automatic and explicit
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isInitialLoad) {
    fetchData(); // Automatic
  }
}, [searchKeyword]);

const handleSearch = () => {
  fetchData(); // Explicit
};
// Result: API called twice (once automatic, once explicit)
```

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Only explicit search
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(); // Initial load only
}, []);

const handleSearch = () => {
  fetchData(); // Only explicit
};
```

### Mistake 5: Not Using useRef for Filters/Search

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: filters in fetchMembers dependencies
const fetchMembers = useCallback(async () => {
  const params = {
    filterUserId: filters.userId, // Direct state access
  };
}, [currentPage, pageSize, filters]); // ❌ filters causes function recreation

// ❌ WRONG: fetchMembers in debounce dependencies
useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setTimeout(() => {
    fetchMembers(); // Direct call
  }, 800);
}, [filters, fetchMembers]); // ❌ fetchMembers causes circular dependency
```

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use refs
const filtersRef = useRef(filters);
useEffect(() => {
  filtersRef.current = filters;
}, [filters]);

const fetchMembers = useCallback(async () => {
  const params = {
    filterUserId: filtersRef.current.userId, // Use ref
  };
}, [currentPage, pageSize]); // ✅ No filters in dependencies

const fetchMembersRef = useRef(fetchMembers);
useEffect(() => {
  fetchMembersRef.current = fetchMembers;
}, [fetchMembers]);

useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setTimeout(() => {
    fetchMembersRef.current(); // Use ref
  }, 800);
}, [filters, isInitialLoad]); // ✅ No fetchMembers in dependencies
```

### Mistake 6: Missing Debounce for Table Filters

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Filters trigger API immediately
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData();
}, [filters]); // ❌ API called on every filter change
```

**Fix:**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Filters with Debounce 800ms
useEffect(() => {
  if (isInitialLoad) return;

  const timer = setTimeout(() => {
    setCurrentPage(1);
    fetchMembersRef.current();
  }, 800);

  return () => clearTimeout(timer);
}, [
  filters.userId,
  filters.userNm /* ... other filter fields */,
  ,
  isInitialLoad,
]);
```

